title: The Ukrainian Anti-Drone Rodeo
description:
Across Ukraine there are anti-air teams, many working in their own backyards, are knocking Shahed Drones out of the sky. As hundreds upon hundreds of of these long range fixed drones careen towards Ukrainian cities, anti-drones teams, many volunteer try to take them out with equipment that varies from brand new western gear, to something that could have been seen in use during their great grandfathers youth. To get a better understanding of their nightly efforts to keep Russian drone attacks at bay, I embedded with soldiers at they worked to defend the Sumy area from drones attacking the city, and en route to other cities like Kyiv.

title: Ukrainian Convicts are Fighting on the Worst Parts of the Front
description:
▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀▀
Outside the city of Toretsk, I embedded with the 59th Mechanized Brigades "Shkval" battalion. This battalion, just like others like it in other brigades across the Ukrainian Armed Forces, are made up of volunteer recruited from the Ukrainian prison system. These convicted criminals are given a choice between severing the rest of their sentence, or waving the remainder of your time behind bars in exchange for military service. This move the authorities in Kyiv, prompted by the acute manpower shortage after over 3 years of full-scale war, has put these men in the position of fighting for both national and personal freedom by trading jumpsuits for pixel camo.

title: Digging Holes is a Dangerous Occupation
description:
Ukrainian engineers are not saved from the dangers of the invasion. Excavators are by combat engineers to dig trenches for infantry to burrow in as shells fly overhead, which would otherwise take much more time and manpower to dig. These excavators are often directly targeted by the enemy, with FPV, artillery, and more targeting these machines as soon as they are spotted. This motivates defending engineers to only operate this heavy equipment when it's too windy or cloudy for drones to effectively work, while flanked by crews with drone jammers and shotguns. You must be on the lookout for those hunting you if you wish to dig.

title: Russia's Human Hunting Ground in Kherson
description:
In the Ukrainian city of Kherson,  the "Human Safari" as many have started calling it, continues to take its toll. While some thought the Russian withdrawal from the city would mean the end of the worst the war has to offer, since Moscow retreated over the Dnipro river, the community has been attacked on a regular basis with semi-constant shelling. Before long, buzzing sounds dominated the air, as drones, grenade dropping and FPV, swarmed the skies above residents homes. These drones would dive at and eliminate not only military targets, but civilian as well. Video after video, often released by Russian drone pilots themselves, show people riding bikes, driving civilian cars, city workers, ambulances, firetrucks, and those walking down street, getting targeted by drones seemingly on the hunt for any signs of life. In order to better understand the "Human Safari" I traveled to Kherson to speak with those caught in the middle of these "Safari" hunts. Including victims of drone attacks, drone pilots, city workers, ambulance crews targeted during rescue missions, engineers preparing the cities defense, and more.

title: Veteran of Kursk Invasion Deserts to Spain after Interview
description:
FULL VIDEO:  https://youtu.be/lVHbaVq_AXs?si=NVBNiDuaFeJCIKkW

I interview Alexander, a Ukrainian artillerymen in the 22nd mechanized brigade, who took part in the invasion of Kursk. He actively supported the attack on the first days through fire support roles, and crossed the border in order to press on the offensive. After being injured, and going on a short leave to spain, he still yearned to be back with his family. And so shortly after this interview, he deserted while on another leave in Spain to stay with his family there. While discussion this desertion with one Ukrainian solider that knew him, he said he was worth many men, and had done immense damage to the enemy while in service. The loss of military experience and manpower to desertion, which did greatly increase in 2024, is a drain on the Ukrainian armed forces they are still trying to solve.

description:

These are the men I got to know during nights embedded with national guard troops defending the Kharkiv region from a renewed offensive.

title: Fighting Wagner in Bakhmut Described by Ukrainian Soldier
description:
The Battle for Bakhmut lasted a good deal longer than the Battle of Stalingrad, despite the relatively low strategic importance of the small city. But in the time the city was fought over, it became a symbol of Ukrainian resistance. But for those who fought for the city, it was more than a symbol. It was one of the most vicious battles the war has seen. Now that the battle for Bakhmut's Urban center has largely ceased, but clashes continue on its outskirts for its surrounding villages, it's a good time to reflect on the battle with those who fought it first hand. So I sat down with Yaroslav, an Ultra Nationalist Right Sector fighter who fought in Bakhmut first hand. In this interview he talks about his thoughts on western analysts wanting Ukraine to withdraw from the city, what it was like fighting the Wagner Group and its prisoner soldiers, Russian tactics, and more.

title: How Ukraine is Using "Meme Bombs" to Win The War
description:
Signmyrocket is a website made by an NGO raising money for the Ukrainian military, but with a twist. They allow for donors to write custom messages of their choosing on shells fired at the Russian army. This has led to a lot of Internet memes, jokes, holiday messages, and more being written on deadly packages launched towards Russian soilders. This has been very successful, and has led to the NGO raising over 1.4 million dollars for Ukraine and it's defenders. So I decided to travel to central Ukraine, where the operation is based, in order to interview the people behind the operation. We explored the history of signing shells, how the operation started, read some of the funniest messages, and even asked about detractors who oppose the fundraising method.
